Yes, in fact, the state I want to check is not in the Tool class, but in a
collection (of CheckedStatements) owned by the tool.

But it doesn&#39;t really matter if the tool contains a hundred getters or one
getter returning another large object (of which class must then be public).
The point is that I don&#39;t want to expose the state at all, but I have to if
I were to test public methods only.

-- 
Jon S Bratseth, Zenior AS

&gt; Bob Koss [mailto:koss@...]
&gt; 
&gt; Are you open to the possibility that your Tool class might need to
&gt; collaborate with other objects (with their own public methods) to do
&gt; its job or are you married to the notion that private methods need
&gt; tests?
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;jon-s&quot; == jon-s bratseth &lt;jon-s.bratseth@...&gt; writes:
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; Consider this counter example i encountered recently when
&gt;     jon-s&gt; making a tool for unit testing store procedures.
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; The tool reads a file containing a test specification, and
&gt;     jon-s&gt; then executes the test. Thus the only public methods I want
&gt;     jon-s&gt; to see is read(file) and execute() throws
&gt;     jon-s&gt; TestFailException.
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; Now, do you think that a sufficient test is to supply some
&gt;     jon-s&gt; working and non-working test spec examples a see if the
&gt;     jon-s&gt; right ones fail? Of course not.
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; In fact, such examples are common in applications which
&gt;     jon-s&gt; contain more complex functionality than data shuffling, and
&gt;     jon-s&gt; the notion than testing public methods is sufficient is
&gt;     jon-s&gt; just plain wrong. Consider simulators, rule engines,
&gt;     jon-s&gt; planners etc.
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; Btw, I don&#39;t like to have my unit tests in the same
&gt;     jon-s&gt; package, but I don&#39;t like the alternative either. What we
&gt;     jon-s&gt; need is a friend construct. Tests commonly needs a backdoor
&gt;     jon-s&gt; to classes, and so does parsistence layers. There is a
&gt;     jon-s&gt; diference between the system level and business level
&gt;     jon-s&gt; interface of classes.
&gt; 
&gt;     jon-s&gt; -- Jon S Bratseth, Zenior AS
&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; -----Opprinnelig melding----- Fra: Miles, Eric SAXONHQ
&gt;     &gt;&gt; [mailto:milese@...] Sendt: 14. mars 2002 23:35 Til:
&gt;     &gt;&gt; &#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39; Emne: RE: [junit] Where to place test
&gt;     &gt;&gt; classes?
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; I&#39;d have to agree with Mr. Rainsberger.  I see no need to test
&gt;     &gt;&gt; methods other than public.  My reasoning is public method types
&gt;     &gt;&gt; are what&#39;s exposed to the public, therefore, test them well.
&gt;     &gt;&gt; If the class is primary used via inheritance, I&#39;ll write test
&gt;     &gt;&gt; methods for the protected methods as well.  Otherwise, I don&#39;t
&gt;     &gt;&gt; bother with private method types.  They&#39;re indirectly tested
&gt;     &gt;&gt; through the methods they support.
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; -----Original Message----- From: J. B. Rainsberger
&gt;     &gt;&gt; [mailto:jbr@...] Sent: Thursday, March 14, 2002
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 5:20 PM To: junit@yahoogroups.com Subject: Re: [junit] Where to
&gt;     &gt;&gt; place test classes?
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; &gt;Another purpose for using JUnit is to create tests &gt;first and
&gt;     &gt;&gt; then write code.  For those that take this &gt;approach to
&gt;     &gt;&gt; development, they would probably want a &gt;test for each method.
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; I&#39;m sorry to be blunt, but absolutely not.
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; In TFP, the goal is to test every feature -- that is, every bit
&gt;     &gt;&gt; of behavior you care about. Implementation details are
&gt;     &gt;&gt; unimportant and, in fact, testing
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; them on their own often impedes refactoring. Since tests are
&gt;     &gt;&gt; meant to provide the &quot;safety net&quot; during refactoring, they
&gt;     &gt;&gt; should try not to get in the way of refactoring, if they can
&gt;     &gt;&gt; avoid it.
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; If you have one feature that uses four or five private methods
&gt;     &gt;&gt; behind a single public method, then it&#39;s best simply to test
&gt;     &gt;&gt; the public method. If you find a bug in there, then that may be
&gt;     &gt;&gt; a clue about your design: perhaps what you perceive as an
&gt;     &gt;&gt; implementation detail is something bigger that should be in its
&gt;     &gt;&gt; own class. At that point, the method becomes public and voila,
&gt;     &gt;&gt; you can test it. (Or package-level, if you prefer that route
&gt;     &gt;&gt; and place your tests in the same package as the production
&gt;     &gt;&gt; code.)
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; &quot;A test for each method&quot; is a bad thing. &quot;Tests for each
&gt;     &gt;&gt; feature or service&quot;
&gt;     &gt;&gt; 
&gt;     &gt;&gt; is a Good Thing.
